1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 HOUSE BILL 3139 By: West (Kevin)
4
5
6 AS INTRODUCED
7 An Act relating to schools; creating the Safeguarding
Personal Expression At K-12 Schools (SPEAKS) Act;
8 defining terms; prohibiting certain student
religious, political, or ideological discrimination;
9 allowing certain protected speech at school regarding
religious, political, or ideological viewpoints;
10 allowing certain gatherings before, during, or after
school; permitting certain clothing and accessories;
11 permitting certain clubs; prohibiting school
discrimination against student clubs; clarifying
12 speech and conduct that schools may prohibit or
restrict; creating private right of action; allowing
13 certain violations to be used as a defense or
counterclaim; prohibiting limitation of legal
14 remedies; providing suit filing limitations;
providing state waiver of immunity; prohibiting
15 schools from being immune for certain violations;
providing for noncodification; providing for
16 codification; and declaring an emergency.
17
18
19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
21 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
22 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Safeguarding
23 Personal Expression At K-12 Schools (SPEAKS) Act".
24
Req. No. 14689 Page 1

1 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 24-166 of Title 70, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. As used in this act:
5 1. "School" means a public school teaching students attending
6 any grade from kindergarten through twelfth grade within an Oklahoma
7 school district; and
8 2. "Student" means an individual who is enrolled at a school on
9 a full-time or part-time basis.
10 B. 1. No student shall be discriminated against or penalized
11 by a school for engaging in religious, political, or ideological
12 speech, or expressing a religious, political, or ideological
13 viewpoint in the same time, place, and manner and to the same extent
14 that other similarly situated students may engage in speech or
15 express views at school.
16 2. A student may engage in protected speech or expression at
17 school, including but not limited to:
18 a. expressing a religious, political, or ideological
19 viewpoint on the topic or subject of discussion or
20 study inside of class,
21 b. expressing religious, political, or ideological
22 viewpoints in a homework assignment, artwork,
23 presentation, or other written or oral assignment
24 without discrimination or academic penalty based on
Req. No. 14689 Page 2

1 the religious, political, or ideological content of
2 the student's submissions. The student's work shall
3 be assessed by ordinary academic standards of
4 substance and relevance and against other legitimate
5 pedagogical concerns identified by the school,
6 c. organizing religious, political, or ideological
7 gatherings before, during, and after school to the
8 same extent and with the same access to school
9 facilities as other student-initiated gatherings are
10 permitted,
11 d. wearing clothing, accessories, and jewelry that
12 display religious, political, or ideological messages
13 or religious, political, or ideological symbols in the
14 same manner and to the same extent that other students
15 are permitted to wear clothing, accessories, and
16 jewelry that display messages and symbols, and
17 e. one or more students organizing religious, political,
18 or ideological clubs before, during, and after school
19 to the same extent and with the same access to school
20 facilities and to all benefits and privileges that are
21 afforded to other clubs authorized by the school. A
22 school shall not discriminate against a student club
23 because of:
24
Req. No. 14689 Page 3

1 (1) the religious, political, or ideological
2 viewpoints expressed by the students or the
3 organization, or
4 (2) any requirement that the leaders or members of
5 the club affirm and adhere to the organization's
6 sincerely held beliefs, comply with the
7 organization's standards of conduct, or further
8 the organization's mission or purpose, as defined
9 by the student organization.
10 C. Nothing in this section shall be interpreted as preventing a
11 school from prohibiting, limiting, or restricting:
12 1. Expression that the First Amendment does not protect
13 including true threats, obscenity, and expression directed to
14 provoke imminent lawless actions or likely to produce such actions;
15 2. Expression that is unwelcome and so severe, pervasive, or
16 subjectively and objectively offensive, that a student is
17 effectively denied equal access to educational opportunities or
18 benefits provided by the school; or
19 3. Conduct that intentionally, materially, and substantially
20 disrupts:
21 a. the operations of the school, or
22 b. the expressive activity of another individual if that
23 activity is occurring in a school space reserved for
24
Req. No. 14689 Page 4

1 that activity under the exclusive use or control of a
2 particular student, group of students, or club.
3 D. 1. Any person or student organization who is harmed by a
4 violation of this act or whose rights under this act are violated
5 shall have a private cause of action against the school for
6 declaratory and injunctive relief, monetary damages, reasonable
7 attorney fees and costs, and any other appropriate relief.
8 2. Any person or student organization aggrieved by a violation
9 of this act may assert such violation as a defense or counterclaim
10 in any disciplinary action or in any civil or administrative
11 proceedings brought against such person or student organization.
12 3. Nothing in this section shall be interpreted to limit any
13 other remedies available by law to any student or student
14 organization.
15 E. A person or student organization shall be required to bring
16 suit for violation of this section not later than two (2) years
17 after the last day the cause of action accrues. For purposes of
18 calculating the two-year limitation period, each day that the
19 violation persists, or each day that a policy in violation of this
20 section remains in effect, shall constitute a new day that the cause
21 of action has accrued.
22 F. The state waives immunity under the Eleventh Amendment of
23 the United States Constitution and consents to suit in a federal
24
Req. No. 14689 Page 5

1 cour t for lawsuits arising out of this act. A school that violates
2 this act is not immune from suit or liability for the violation.
3 SECTION 3. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
4 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
5 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
6 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
